INSERT INTO `wp_dyfl_posts` VALUES("510","1","2013-03-14 10:51:10","2013-03-14 16:51:10","<a href=\"http://www.frontenactennis.com/wow-its-mats-wilander-here-in-st-louis/mats-our-shot/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-512\"><img class=\" wp-image-512 alignleft\" alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.frontenactennis.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/Mats-our-shot-275x332.jpg\" width=\"248\" height=\"299\" /></a>Mats and his business partner, Cameron Lickle, will play an exhibition match against Terry and Stefan on Saturday afternoon, right after the Doubles Classic final.

Want to know more about their WOW program? Here\'s a <a href=\"http://wp.me/a2SC2L-8j\" target=\"_blank\">pdf brochure</a> you can download.
<h2>About Mats.</h2>
A former No. 1 player from Sweden, he won seven Grand Slam singles titles from 1982 through 1988:
<ul>
	<li>Three at the French Open.</li>
	<li>Three at the Australian Open.</li>
	<li>One at the US Open.</li>
</ul>
He also won a Wimbledon doubles title in that same period.
<h3>A winner on every surface.</h3>
In 1988, he won three of the four Grand Slam singles events - everything but Wimbledon - and wound up the year ranked No. 1. And while Mats never did win Wimbledon in singles, he did win the Australian Open when that tournament was still played on grass. That makes him one of just five men to win Grand Slam singles titles on all three surfaces: grass, clay and hard courts. The other four are Jimmy Connors, Andre Agassi, Rafael Nadal and Roger Federer. And he and Nadal are the only two men ever to have won at least two Grand Slam singles titles on all three surfaces.

What\'s more, when Mats won his fourth Grand Slam title, he was just 20 years old - the youngest man in history to reach that milestone.
<h3>Mats in the Davis Cup.</h3>
In the Davis Cup for Sweden, Wilander\'s record is 36-16 in singles and 7-2 in doubles. But his most memorable Davis Cup match came in defeat, in what is still the longest match in Cup history. And it happened right here in St. Louis, on carpet, against John McEnroe, in 1982. The final score: 9-7, 6-2, 15-17, 3-6, 8-6. the match lasted a grueling six hours and 32 minutes.
<h3>Don\'t miss Mats and Cameron on Saturday, May 18.</h3>
Tickets are just $10/person or $15 for your whole family!

