INSERT INTO `wp_dyfl_posts` VALUES("1821","1","2016-04-29 17:10:42","2016-04-30 00:10:42","<div class=\"big\"><a href=\"http://www.frctennis.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/Cobb-book-InBag.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1822\" src=\"http://www.frctennis.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/Cobb-book-InBag.jpg\" alt=\"Book: Ron Cobb, St. Louis Tennis Memories\" width=\"1200\" height=\"900\" /></a></div>

<div class=\"copy\">
<h2>Journalist/Hall-of-Famer Ron Cobb has your local tennis history right here!</h2>
<!---more--->
<h3>It’s all in his new book – only at String ’n Swing.</h3>
Former St. Louis Post-Dispatch tennis writer Ron Cobb has collected his favorite tennis stories in a new book, <em>St. Louis Tennis Memories. </em>Taking a step beyond his original reporting at the time, the book also updates us on a number of the people featured in the articles, showing us where they are now.

Himself a recent inductee into the St. Louis Tennis Hall of Fame, Ron tracked down former St. Louis champions from Florida to California – and Australia – for his updates, which include Jim Parker, Bob McKinley, Leo Estopare, Jennifer Prah, Juan Farrow, Bruce Foxworth, Todd Hammonds, Blair and Mary Ellen Strassner, Toby Clark, Chris Gillis, Siri Eklund, Mauricio Sovero, Laura Guignon and dozens more.

The book also features an index of more than 850 names of St. Louis people mentioned in the stories. If you played tournaments in the ’80s or ’90s, your name might be there!

String \'n Swing is also the new home of the St. Louis Tennis Hall of Fame, which was previously housed at the Triple A Club, and showcases a display of more than 500 vintage tennis ball cans from the private collection of Bill Tao, who acquired them over several decades in his travels around the world.

You can find the book only at String \'n Swing Tennis (314-995-6860), a shop that opened in March in Old Frontenac Square. That\'s on the northwest corner of Lindbergh and German Blvds., next door to The Shack.

